1. Initialize variables to keep track of the count of zeroes and ones.
2. Iterate through the string using a for loop.
3. Update the count of zeroes and ones based on the current character.
4. If the count of zeroes is greater than the count of ones, update the maximum length variable.
5. If the counts are equal, break the loop as the substring is balanced.
6. Return the maximum length found.

This solution has a time complexity of O(n) because we iterate through the string once. The space complexity is O(1) as we only use a constant amount of space for the variables countZero, countOne, and maxLength. The energy implications are low as the algorithm only performs a single pass through the string and uses minimal resources.

